    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Startled goblin\" is just a colorful way of describing someone in a rush, my friend! When you get into the thick of city transit, you start behaving like one of those frantic little creatures trying to sneak past a grumpy troll. You absolutely should worry about the bus timing, especially if the weather is foul. Give yourself a solid 25 to 35 minutes buffer between your LNER arrival and your local bus departure in Edinburgh.\n\nThis buffer is crucial because Edinburgh's city buses can be subject to traffic snarls, and you don't want to be stranded waiting in the downpour. It's much better to wait a few minutes on a bus stop bench than to have the misery of a missed connection while soaked through. You can always catch the next bus, but missing a connection feels worse than a minor delay, right? Just like when those goblins finally decide to stop raiding the village and start complaining about the rain themselves!\n\nIf you know the bus route beforehand, check if it operates frequently, which is usually the case in a city, but always factor in a little extra time for the *actual* journey time. Think of it this way: the LNER is the main, reliable beast",
      "source": "target",
